            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@justinmk \r\n> why auto instead of no\r\n\r\nmy reasoning was: as far as I know, sings are not used in Vim *by default*, and therefore they only appear when user **explicitly configures them** (e.g. installs a plugin for that purpose). I only know about plugins that use signs for editable files (integration of git repos) or specific filetypes (integration of linters, compilers, build systems). So:\r\n- in all situations that I can imagine, signcolumn is empty anyway in ft=man, so no difference between `auto` and `no`\r\n- if by any chance there ARE some signs for ft=man, then user must have made an explicit **effort** to add them, and they could be annoyed by the fact that signs are still not visible.\r\n\r\nOn the other side, the bad scenario for this decision (using auto instead of no) is when user (1) has signcolumn=no in their global config AND (2) still creates some signs when browsing man pages (maybe unintentionally, with a plugin). It may be annoying for them to suddenly see the signcolumn, given that they have explicitly disabled it in `init.vim`. Regarding this case:\r\n1. I'm fine with signcolumn=no if anyone believes it is better.\r\n2. A more clever solution could be to check the current value of signcolumn and only downgrade from \"yes\" to \"auto\", but keep the original value otherwise. This is more in line with the motivation of the proposed change — in reality, I only wanted to prevent signcolumn from being \"yes\" (which may be good as a global value, but bad for ft=man).\r\n\r\nI'm equally ready to implement any of these two approaches, or keep the current one.",
            "commit_id": "2c160f39d3299ff7f9853e4856cefff567f8fbde",
            "created_at": "2024-06-13T21:49:26Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -8,14 +8,16 @@ let b:did_ftplugin = 1\n \n setlocal noexpandtab tabstop=8 softtabstop=8 shiftwidth=8\n setlocal wrap breakindent linebreak\n+setlocal colorcolumn=0 nolist\n \n \" Parentheses and '-' for references like `git-ls-files(1)`; '@' for systemd\n \" pages; ':' for Perl and C++ pages.  Here, I intentionally omit the locale\n \" specific characters matched by `@`.\n setlocal iskeyword=@-@,:,a-z,A-Z,48-57,_,.,-,(,)\n \n-setlocal nonumber norelativenumber\n-setlocal foldcolumn=0 colorcolumn=0 nolist nofoldenable\n+\" man page content is likely preformatted for the terminal width, so\n+\" narrowing display by any additional columns leads to Embarrassing Line Wrap\n+setlocal nonumber norelativenumber foldcolumn=0 signcolumn=auto",
